            <div class="ag-label">The Rhythm Library System</div>
            <h2>A lifetime of teaching distilled into one method</h2>
            <p>The Rhythm Library System is the product of Gordy's decades of experience as both a performer and educator. It takes an idea that has existed in drum pedagogy for years — applying rudimental sticking patterns to the solo pages from Ted Reed's <em>Syncopation</em> — and transforms it into a <strong>complete, organized practice system</strong>.</p>
            <p>Gordy's key insight was that you could <strong>eliminate the rest patterns</strong> from the traditional approach and still achieve the same results using only the note patterns: half note, dotted quarter, quarter note, and eighth note. This simplification made the system more accessible without reducing its effectiveness.</p>
            <p>He then created a catalog — a <strong>Library</strong> — of simple two and four bar rhythmic phrases that combine only two or three note values at a time. These simpler combinations proved more musically useful and just as effective as applying all four patterns to complex rhythms.</p>
            <p>The result is a system that a beginner can start using on their first week of lessons and an advanced player can spend years exploring.</p>
